[Black "Qb3 Slav Repertoire"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3
{ It's not a secret that the Slav Defense is one of Black's most reliable openings against 1. d4. Moreover, Black has a wide choice of different variations such as the Classical Slav, the Semi-Slav, the Chebanenko Slav, the Schlechter variation, etc. Throughout my career as a chess player my main choice against the Slav was 3. Nf3 and 4. Nc3, entering mainstream lines. It goes without saying that I had to be ready to deal with all of Black's various options, whether it was the Classical Slav, Semi-Slav or Chebanenko. All of these variations have been played quite a lot on top Grandmaster level and therefore the theory has been evolving all the time.At some point I felt that it was necessary to develop an alternative variation, which wouldn't require a lot of theoretical knowledge, but would nevertheless be challenging. My choice has fallen upon the 4. Qb3 variation. It's important to mention that I employ this move only after 3... Nf6, while Black can deviate by playing the 'Triangle Slav' 3... e6 after which 4. Qb3 doesn't appeal to me as much.The 4. Qb3 variation has served me pretty well since 1998. Since the theory of this line has significantly evolved, I am very excited finally to introduce my work in this variation. It's important to add that 4. Qb3 is very different from the lines I recommend in my Grandmaster Repertoire series. I hope that chess players all over the World will enjoy my work and, even more importantly, score a lot of wins in this line.Boris Avrukh, March 2020 }
